{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477096","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477096"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:57:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:57:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14177"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14177","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14177"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.19,0.04,0.06,0.63]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6860"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55574"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6860","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6860"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14177"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41114"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2040"},{"type":"tags","id":"2992"},{"type":"tags","id":"3320"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5820"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15630"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44200"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44885"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55574","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55574"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA seven-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department after falling from a height of about two metres while playing on a jungle gym. He complains of neck pain and tingling in both arms. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed with a pulse rate of 110/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. His neck is tender to palpation, and he has decreased sensation to light touch in both arms. Motor strength is 4/5 in all limbs. Cervical spine X-rays and CT scan show no fractures or dislocations.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cervical spine flexion-extension views","Immediate neurosurgical consultation","Discharge home with neck brace and follow-up","Admit for observation without further imaging","MRI of the cervical spine"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a scenario highly suspicious for spinal cord injury without radiological abnormality (SCIWORA), a condition more common in children due to their increased ligamentous laxity and anatomical differences in the spine compared to adults. The patient\u0027s mechanism of injury, neck pain, and neurological symptoms (tingling and decreased sensation in the arms) are concerning, especially given the normal X-ray and CT findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI of the cervical spine\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step in management. MRI is the imaging modality of choice for suspected SCIWORA as it can detect spinal cord oedema, contusion, or other soft tissue injuries not visible on X-ray or CT. Early detection is crucial for appropriate management and prognosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDischarge home with neck brace and follow-up\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate given the patient\u0027s neurological symptoms. This could potentially lead to worsening of a spinal cord injury if present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdmit for observation without further imaging\u003C/strong\u003E is insufficient. While admission and close monitoring are important, further imaging with MRI is necessary to evaluate for spinal cord injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate neurosurgical consultation\u003C/strong\u003E may be necessary depending on the MRI findings, but it is not the most appropriate next step. The diagnosis needs to be confirmed with MRI before specialist consultation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECervical spine flexion-extension views\u003C/strong\u003E are contraindicated in this scenario. With the suspicion of spinal cord injury, any movement of the neck could potentially worsen the injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter obtaining the MRI, management would typically include continued spinal immobilisation, consideration of high-dose corticosteroids (though this remains controversial), and close neurological monitoring. The patient should be admitted for observation and may require prolonged immobilisation depending on the MRI findings and clinical course. Neurosurgical consultation would be appropriate once the MRI results are available.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Spinal cord injury without radiological abnormality (SCIWORA) is more common in children due to their increased ligamentous laxity and anatomical differences.","MRI is the imaging modality of choice for suspected SCIWORA as it can detect spinal cord edema or contusion not visible on X-ray or CT.","Initial management of suspected SCIWORA includes spinal immobilisation, consideration of corticosteroids, and close neurological monitoring."],"references":["Szwedowski D, Walecki J. Spinal Cord Injury without Radiographic Abnormality (SCIWORA) - Clinical and Radiological Aspects. Pol J Radiol. 2014 Dec 8;79:461-4. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4262055/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41114"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14177"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41114","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41114"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-16T20:12:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-16T20:13:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6860"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55574"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"32","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/32"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurosurgery","synonyms":null,"descript